  "prompt": "What is the difference between foreign bonds and Eurobonds?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between foreign bonds and Eurobonds:\n\nForeign Bonds:\n1. Issued in a foreign country's domestic market\n2. Denominated in the local currency of that country\n3. Typically sold to investors in that specific country\n4. Subject to local regulatory requirements\n5. Example: A US company issuing bonds in Japan in Japanese yen\n\nEurobonds:\n1. Issued internationally outside the issuer's home country\n2. Usually denominated in a currency different from the issuer's home currency\n3. Sold in multiple international markets\n4. Less regulated and more flexible\n5. Typically traded in international financial centers\n6. Example: A US company issuing bonds in dollars in London\n\nKey distinctions:\n- Market of issuance\n- Currency denomination\n- Regulatory environment\n- Investor base\n- Trading flexibility\n\nBoth are types of international bonds but have different characteristics and target different investor markets. Eurobonds generally offer more international flexibility and broader market access compared to traditional foreign bonds.",
